Chuck,

I think your criticism is unwarranted.  First of all, I find JUnit to be a
wonderful help and I&#39;m very glad to have it.  Second, the JUnit classloader
DOES work.  I don&#39;t know what&#39;s going on within org.w3c.dom.Document, but in
general, when the -noloading switch solves the problem it indicates that
some part of the software is using a different class loader and that results
in an object mismatch.  The response to this is to disable JUnit&#39;s reloading
class loader and use the default one (which will not reload changed classes)
that the software under test is expecting.  Is this a bad design decision?
Do you have a better solution to this problem?

 - George

-----Original Message-----
From: Herrick, Chuck [mailto:chuck.herrick@...]
Sent: Tuesday, March 27, 2001 8:37 AM
To: &#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;
Subject: RE: [junit] cannot run testing with UI TestRunner?



Take a look at the security machinations that Java demands the classloader
undergo on behalf of the virtual machine. 

I would say that if JUnit can&#39;t complete some very fundamental piece of its
business because the authors made bad design decisions regarding the
classloader, you&#39;d need to get someone to go back and refactor JUnit.

Perhaps someone should have tested JUnit with some test software before
rolling it out. 


